metadata.name: Neo-Retro Building #31
metadata.description:
"Depicting architectural"

The idea of depicting architectural designs for buildings in the future dates back to the 19th century with the rise of industrialization and advancements in technology. Architects and artists began to imagine what cities and buildings of the future might look like, often featuring towering skyscrapers, flying cars, and sleek, modern designs.

One early example is the 1889 World's Fair in Paris, which featured a "City of the Future" exhibit that showcased a vision of a highly-developed, technologically advanced metropolis. In the early 20th century, architects such as Le Corbusier proposed designs for "machine for living" buildings that were meant to be efficient and functional, with an emphasis on clean lines and minimal ornamentation.

In the decades that followed, architects and designers continued to create images of future buildings and cities, with an increasing focus on sustainability and eco-friendliness. This can be seen in concepts like the "smart city," which envisions cities that are highly connected and responsive to the needs of citizens, and designs for buildings that incorporate renewable energy sources and green spaces.

metadata.name: Tema #40
metadata.description:
Tema is the second in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

After gaining some traction with his original collection RAM, Zajec and his collaborating programmer Matjaz Hmeljak undertook a more complex algorithm titled "The Cube: Theme and Variation" (or TVC). The program laid out 8 unique elements in a grid, creating a three-dimensional viewing of objects in space. They published a paper about the underlying algorithm, found at: http://www.edwardzajec.com/tvc4/pil1/index.html

TVC was first printed in 1971, shortly after Zajec returned to Italy following his artistic studies in the US. It was programmed on an IBM 9044 & printed with a CalComp 563 plotter.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Perspective #44
metadata.description:
A few primitives and a lot of points.

Warning: This piece is GPU intensive, it may not render on lower end devices.

Keys
s: Take a screenshot
space: Pause/Play the animation.
r: Play a new animation
↑: Increase point alpha
↓: Decrease point alpha
→: Increase point density
←: Decrease point density

URL Params
w: Width of the canvas - (ex, w=1024) - [0-2048]
h: Height of the canvas - (ex, h=1024) - [0-2048]
a: To set the alpha for the points - [0.0-1.0]
p: To set the total number of points to draw (in millions) [1-8]
s: Make the visual static - (ex, s=1)

metadata.name: FAT Christmas #682
metadata.description:
“FAT Christmas” 由三位台灣創作者主導，並且與另外幾位創作者共創部件。包含發行過 Moonlight Impression 的 mido、影像創作者 Graphyni、熱衷 AI 生成的 Fagem。
你可以在這個生成器中獲取 Chang Ming Yao 的 Aka’s Ape 或由 Chi.L 繪製的 AKAZOO Cat，甚至是 roupin_art 的 Dino Ali。
並祝福所有 Tezos 的創作者與藏家，接下來一年能充滿希望。

我們竭盡所能的補充多樣性，確保每次鑄造都是明確且獨特的結果。
在30多種的背景中，包含由創作者提供的特殊款式，如果你足夠幸運，將有機會獲得美麗且獨特的角色 。

角色方面：
Aka’s Ape 包含 8 種 character、8 種 eyes、8 種 mouth、3 種 personality。
Aka Zoo Cat 包含 7 種 character、10 種 eyes、7 種 mouth、5 種  personality。
Dino Ali 包含 26 種 character、5 種 eyes、8 種 mouth、6 種 personality。
所有角色共享超過 20 款頭飾、9 款服裝、10 種服裝印花。
角色前方桌面的三個位置，亦各自包含 10 種以上的配件。

由衷的希望各位都能玩得開心。
祝大家聖誕快樂，新年快樂。

“FAT Christmas” is a collabration of three creators from Taiwan, with parts contributed by creators including mido's “Moonlight Impression”, video creator Graphyni and generative AI enthusiast Fagem.
You can get Aka’s Ape by Chang Ming Yao, AKAZOO  Cat by Chi.L and Dino Ali by roupin_art from the generator.
Blessing to all Tezos creators and collectors, filled with hope in the coming year.

Diversity is replenished in our best effort to ensure apparent and unique results in every mint.
Among over 30 different backgrounds, including special design provided by the creators, you will have a chance to get a gorgeous and unique character if you are lucky enough.

About the characters:
Aka’s Ape includes 8 types of character, 8 types of eyes, 8 types of mouth and 3 types of personality.
Aka Zoo Cat includes 7 types of character, 10 types of eyes, 7 types of mouth and 5 types of personality.
Dino Ali includes 26 types of character, 5 types of eyes, 8 types of mouth and 6 types of personality.
All characters share over 20 headwears, 9 clothes and 10 clothes patterns.
Over 10 decorations will be assigned to 3 positions on the table in front of the character.

Sincerely hope everyone can have fun.
And wishing you all a Merry Christmas and a happy new year.

metadata.name: Punktwelt #516
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: (Dis)ordered loom #64
metadata.description:
"Disordered loom" continues my exploration on texture, points, lines and noise, now in a grid within a grid. With the 'r' key you can toggle between an ordered and disordered loom, the disorder is created by an assigned subset of 4 sets of rotations. With the 't' key you can toggle translation, an additional movement is added/subtracted. With the 'e' key you can toggle more entropy.

You can further self-curate your token by clicking the canvas, colours change with each click, with the 'c' key you can remove a colour, you can press 'c' until two colours remain, with the 'v' key you can reset colours.

With the 'm' key you can mix all possible textures, press 'm' again to switch to your assigned texture. 

With the '+'/'-' keys you can alter the grain, "Disordered loom" implements the p5.grain addon.

Press 'e' to toggle entropy
Press 'r' to toggle between ordered/disordered loom
Press 't' to toggle translation
Press 'm' for mixed textures mode
Press 'c' to remove a color
Press 'v' to reset colors
Press '+'/'-' to alter the grain
Press 's' to save a png image
Press 'j' to save a jpg image
Press 'x' to save a higher resolution png
